id: format-spec
title: TNL file format specification document
scope: feature
owners: [@jana]
paths: [docs/tnl-format.md]
surfaces: [docs/tnl-format.md]
dependencies: [parser, resolve, verify]

intent:
  `docs/tnl-format.md` is the adopter-facing authoritative reference
  for the TNL file format. It describes every field the parser
  recognizes, how clauses are classified, what the sidecar contains,
  and how the verifier interprets each classification. Deferred from
  A1 so the doc reflects the parser's actual shipped behavior rather
  than its intent.

behaviors:
  - `docs/tnl-format.md` MUST exist and be written in markdown.
  - The doc MUST contain section headings covering, in order: Overview; File layout; Machine zone fields; Contract zone (behaviors); Clause classification; Human zone; Scope; Dependencies; Sidecar; Verification tiers; Edit-vs-new guidance; Examples.
  - The Machine zone section MUST document each field (`id`, `title`, `scope`, `owners`, `paths`, `surfaces`, `dependencies`) including required-vs-optional status and the validation the parser applies.
  - The Contract zone section MUST document RFC 2119 keywords (MUST, MUST NOT, SHOULD, SHOULD NOT, MAY) and the four clause classes: `structural`, `test-backed`, `semantic`, `advisory`.
  - The Clause classification section MUST document the `[semantic]` prefix and the `[test: <file>::<name>]` prefix, and MUST state that the two prefixes are mutually exclusive (parser rejects a clause carrying both).
  - The Sidecar section MUST document the on-disk shape of `tnl/.resolved/<id>.meta.json`: `unit_hash`, per-clause `id`/`hash`/`class`, optional `test: { file, name }` on `test-backed` clauses, `resolved_at`. MUST note that `resolved_at` is preserved byte-for-byte across runs when `unit_hash` is unchanged.
  - The Verification tiers section MUST document tier 1 (paths-exist, dependencies-resolve) and tier 2 (literal-string search for `[test:]` name in the named file; no test execution). MUST note tier 3 is deferred.
  - The Edit-vs-new section MUST name (a) when a new TNL is justified and (b) when to edit an existing one, matching the `CLAUDE.md` stanza's subsection.
  - The Examples section MUST contain at least two complete TNL files as fenced code blocks: one `scope: feature` and one `scope: repo-wide`.
  - Every fenced TNL code block in the doc MUST parse successfully via `parseTnl()` — a doc containing an unparseable example is broken.
  - The doc MUST reference the parser entry point (`src/parser.ts`), the resolver (`src/resolver.ts`), and the verifier (`src/verifier.ts`) as cross-refs.
  - Tests MUST cover: `docs/tnl-format.md` exists; each required section heading is present in order; every fenced-tnl code block extracts cleanly and parses via `parseTnl()` without error; the doc contains the strings "MUST", "SHOULD", "MAY", "[semantic]", "[test:", "structural", "test-backed", "semantic", "advisory".

non-goals:
  - A formal EBNF grammar — plain-English aligned with the parser's actual acceptance is clearer for adopters; EBNF can land post-v1 if needed.
  - Describing tier 3 semantic verification in detail — tier 3 is deferred post-v1; the doc names it as a deferred extension only.
  - Covering every MCP tool's wire schema — those live in the MCP SDK output; the doc only names the MCP integration.
  - Migration guide from other contract formats — no prior format to migrate from.
  - Comparison with alternative specs (RFC, OpenAPI, etc.) — the doc stands alone; comparative analysis belongs in a blog post, not a spec.

rationale:
  Why deferred from A1 to B5: writing the spec against a shipped
  parser means every sentence can be verified against working code.
  An A1 spec would describe intent, and drift by A7 would produce
  a doc that doesn't match reality.

  Why a `parseTnl()`-validity test on every fenced code block: keeps
  the doc in lockstep with the parser. If the parser tightens a
  check or renames a field, an outdated example in the doc fails
  the test and forces the fix.

  Why a single `docs/` directory rather than a dedicated docs site:
  single-file reference is easier to grep, less moving machinery,
  sufficient for v1. A docs site is a release decision once adopter
  feedback says it's needed.
